# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chrysler-new-yorker
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/1973-opec-oil-embargo-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] The **American Antiquarian Society** (**AAS**), located in Worcester, Massachusetts, is a learned society and a national research library of pre-twentieth-century American history and culture.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] Founded in 1812, it is the oldest historical society in the United States with a national focus.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] Its main building, known as Antiquarian Hall, is a U.S.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] National Historic Landmark in recognition of this legacy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] The mission of the AAS is to collect, preserve and make available for study all printed records of what is now known as the United States of America.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] This includes materials from the first European settlement through the year 1900.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] The collections of the AAS contain over four million books, pamphlets, newspapers, periodicals, graphic arts materials and manuscripts.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] The Society is estimated to hold copies of two-thirds of the total books known to have been printed in what is now the United States from the establishment of the first press in 1640 through the year 1820; many of these volumes are exceedingly rare and a number of them are unique.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] Historic materials from all fifty U.S. states, most of Canada and the British West Indies are included in the AAS repository.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] An act of congress requires that one copy of the journals of the Senate and of the House of Representatives along with other documents are to be transmitted to the Governor of Massachusetts for the use and benefit of the Society.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] One of the more notable volumes held by the Society is a copy of the first book printed in America, the Bay Psalm Book.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] AAS has one of the largest collections of newspapers printed in America through 1876, with more than two million issues in its collection.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] On the initiative of Isaiah Thomas, the AAS was founded on October 24, 1812, through an act of the Massachusetts General Court.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] It was the third historical society established in America, and the first to be national in its scope.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] Isaiah Thomas started the collection with approximately 8,000 books from his personal library.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] The first library building was erected in 1820 in downtown Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] In 1853, the Society moved its collections to a larger building at the corner of Highland Street, also in Worcester.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] This building was later abandoned and another new building was constructed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] Designed by Winslow, Bigelow & Wadsworth, the Georgian Revival building was completed in 1910 and stands on the corner of Park Avenue and Salisbury Street.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] There have been several additions to this building to accommodate the growing collection.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] The most recent addition was completed in 2019 and created room for an updated HVAC system, conservation lab, and multi-use learning lab.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] AAS was presented with the 2013 National Humanities Medal by President Obama in a ceremony at the White House.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] As part of AAS's mission as a learned society, it offers a variety of public lectures and seminars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] One topic to which AAS dedicates significant academic energies is printing technology, especially in 18th century British North America.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] Since Isaiah Thomas was a newspaper man himself, he collected a large number of printed materials.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] With regard to printing, paper making, edition setting, and reprinting, not much had changed in European technology by the eighteenth century.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] It was not until the late eighteenth century that paper-making material began to evolve from a hand-woven cloth to an industrial pulp.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] AAS undertakes special efforts to preserve printed records from this time period, as the Society maintains an on-site conservation department with various sewing, cloth, and binding materials to aid in the preservation process.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] Over its two-hundred-year history, the Society has had 14 formal leaders who have shaped the organization's vision, collections, and day-to-day operations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] Leadership roles at the AAS have historically overlapped in chronology, as different roles oversaw different aspects of the Society simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-antiquarian-society] The American Antiquarian Society's membership includes scholars, writers, journalists, historians, artists, filmmakers, collectors, American presidents, and civic leaders.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' most similar competitors were those automakers that held similar annual sales levels, such as Studebaker, Packard, Kaiser Motors, and Willys-Overland.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Their largest competitors were the Big Three—Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] After periods of intermittent independent success, Renault acquired a significant interest in American Motors in 1979, and the company was ultimately acquired by Chrysler in 1987.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1954, Nash-Kelvinator Corporation began the acquisition of the Hudson Motor Car Company (in what was called a merger).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new corporation would be called the American Motors Corporation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] An earlier corporation with the same name, co-founded by Louis Chevrolet, had existed in Plainfield, New Jersey, from 1916 through 1922 before merging into the Bessemer–American Motors Corporation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new company retained Hudson CEO A.E.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Barit as a consultant and he took a seat on the board of directors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason, the architect of the merger, believed that the survival of the U.S.'s remaining independent automakers depended on their joining to form one multiple-brand company capable of challenging the Big Three as an equal.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "frantic 1953–54 Ford/GM price war" devastated the remaining "independent" automakers.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The reasons for the merger between Nash and Hudson included helping cut costs and strengthen their sales organizations to meet the intense competition expected from autos' Big Three.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] One quick result from the merger was the doubling up with Nash on purchasing and production, allowing Hudson to cut prices an average of $155 on the Wasp line, and up to $204 on the more expensive Hornet models.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the merger, AMC had its first profitable quarter during the second three months of 1955, earning $1,592,307, compared to a loss of $3,848,667 during the same period in the previous year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason also entered into informal discussions with James J.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nance of Packard to outline his strategic vision.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Interim plans were made for American Motors to buy Packard Ultramatic automatic transmissions and Packard V8 engines for certain American Motors products.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1954, Packard acquired Studebaker.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new Studebaker-Packard Corporation (S-P) made the new 320 cu in (5.2 L) Packard V8 engine and Packard's Ultramatic automatic transmission available to American Motors for its 1955 Nash Ambassador and Hudson Hornet models.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ironically, Romney had once been offered Nance's job.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1948, Romney received offers from Packard for the post of chief operating officer and from Nash for the number two position in the company.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the Packard offer would have paid more, Romney decided to work under Mason because he thought Nash had a brighter future.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Mason and Nance had agreed that S-P would endeavor to purchase parts from American Motors in return, but S-P did not do so.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] As the Packard engines and transmissions were comparatively expensive, American Motors began development of its own V8.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also spent US$40 million developing its Double Safe Single Unit monocoque, which debuted in the 1956 model year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In mid-1956, the 352 cu in (5.8 L) Packard V8 and TwinUltramatic transmission were phased out and replaced by American Motors's new V8 and by GM Hydra-Matic and Borg-Warner transmissions.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors combined the Nash and Hudson product lines under a common manufacturing strategy in 1955, with the production of Nashes and Hudsons consolidated at the Nash plant in Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Detroit Hudson plant was converted to military contract production and eventually sold.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The separate Nash and Hudson dealer networks were retained.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudsons were redesigned to harmonize with Nash's body styles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fast-selling Nash Rambler model was sold as a Nash and a Hudson in 1955 and 1956.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] These badge-engineered Ramblers, and similarly the small Metropolitans, were identical except for the hubcaps, nameplates, and other minor trim.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The pre-existing full-size Nash product line was continued with the Nash Statesman restyled as the "new" Hudson Wasp and the Nash Ambassador restyled as the Hudson Hornet.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the cars shared the same body shell, they were at least as different from one another as Chevrolet and Pontiac.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudsons and Nashes each used their engines as they had previously: the Hudson Hornet continued to offer the 308 cu in (5.0 L) I6 that had powered the (NASCAR) champion during the early 1950s; the Wasp now used the former engine of the Hudson Jet.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash Ambassador and Statesman continued with overhead- valve and L-head sixes, respectively.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Hudson and Nash cars had different front suspensions.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Trunk lids were interchangeable, but other body panels, rear window glass, dash panels, and braking systems differed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hudson Hornet, Wasp, and their Nash counterparts had improved ride, visibility, and fuel economy because of their lighter unitized Nash body.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The larger Nash and Hudson range did not sell well, and AMC lost money each year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dismayed with the results, Romney decided in 1956 that the company's future lay with the compact Rambler line.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney halted production on the new large cars and focused entirely on the new Rambler Six and V8 introducing them in 1956, despite being scheduled for a 1957 release.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of the new Ramblers were poor, and sales of the Hudson and Nash models were almost non-existent, resulting in a $31.7 million operating loss for 1956.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales improved in 1957, but the company saw a $11.8 million loss.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response, Romney launched a massive public relations campaign, traveling 70,000 miles (112,654 kilometres) nationwide in 12 months.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney spoke at union halls, dinners, churches, fairgrounds, and radio and TV stations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] He was anywhere where he could get the word out about Rambler.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Rambler sales took off in 1958, up 58.7%, and 425 new dealers were signed up.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, 1958 became AMC's first year of profitability since its formation, with $28 million in earnings.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Nash and Hudson brands were dropped, and Rambler became a marque in its own right and the mainstay of the company.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The popular British-built Metropolitan subcompact continued as a standalone brand until it was discontinued in 1961.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The prototype 1958 Nash Ambassador/Hudson Hornet, built on a stretched Rambler platform, was renamed at the last minute as "Ambassador by Rambler".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] To round out the model line, American Motors reintroduced the previous 1955, 100 in (2,540 mm) wheelbase Nash Rambler as the new Rambler American with only a few modifications.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Rambler a compact lineup that included the reintroduced American, the 108 in (2,743 mm) wheelbase Rambler Six and Rebel V8, as well as the 117 in (2,972 mm) wheelbase Ambassador.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of Ramblers soared in the late 1950s partly because of American Motors' focus on the compact car and its marketing efforts.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] These included sponsoring the hugely popular Walt Disney anthology television series and as an exhibitor at the Disneyland theme park in Anaheim, California.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] George Romney himself pitched the Rambler product in television commercials.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the "Big Three" introduced ever-larger cars, American Motors followed a "dinosaur-fighter" strategy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's leadership focused the company on the compact car, a fuel-efficient vehicle 20 years before there was a real need for them.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This gave Romney a high profile in the media.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Two core strategic factors came into play: (1) the use of shared components in American Motors products and (2) a refusal to participate in the Big Three's restyling race.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This cost-control policy helped Rambler develop a reputation for building solid economy cars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Company officials were confident in the changing market and in 1959 announced a $10 million (US$110,445,205 today) expansion of its Kenosha complex (to increase annual straight-time capacity from 300,000 to 440,000 cars).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors was also beginning to experiment with non-gasoline-powered automobiles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] On April 1, 1959, American Motors and Sonotone Corporation announced a joint research effort to consider producing an electric car that was to be powered by a "self-charging" battery.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sonotone had the technology for making sintered plate nickel–cadmium batteries that can be recharged very rapidly and are lighter than a typical automobile lead–acid battery.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1959, American Motors hired designer Dick Teague, who had previously worked for General Motors, Packard, and Chrysler; after Edmund E.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Anderson left the company in 1961, Teague was named principal designer and in 1964, vice president.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] To stay competitive, American Motors produced a wide range of products during the 1960s and added innovations long before the "Big Three" introduced them.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] For example, the Rambler Classic was equipped with a standard tandem master cylinder in 1962 that provided stopping ability even if there was a failure in the brake system.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Only Cadillac also included this safety feature six years before U.S. safety regulations required it on all cars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automotive industry, American Motors offered adjustable front seat backrests from their Nash-origin, and in 1964, the Classic and Ambassador were equipped with standard dual reclining front seats nearly a decade before the Big Three offered them as options.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Bendix disc brakes were made standard on the Marlin and optional on other models in 1965.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made the Marlin one of the first modern American cars with standard disc brakes, while the Big Three did not offer them until the early 1970s on most of their models to meet Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the early part of the decade, sales were strong, thanks in no small part to the company's history of building small cars, which came into vogue in 1961.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In both 1960 and 1961, Ramblers ranked in third place among U.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] S. automobile sales, up from third on the strength of small-car sales, even in the face of a lot of new competition.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Romney's strategic focus was very successful, as reflected in the firm's healthy profits year after year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company became completely debt-free.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The financial success allowed the company to reach an agreement on August 26, 1961, with the United Auto Workers for a profit sharing plan that was new in the automobile industry.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its new three-year labor contract included generous annual improvement pay increases, and automatic cost-of-living raises.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, in 1962, Romney resigned to run for Governor of Michigan.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] His replacement was Roy Abernethy, American Motors' successful sales executive.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] By 1964, Studebaker production in the United States had ended, and its Canadian operations ceased in 1966.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The "Big Three", plus the smaller American Motors, Kaiser Jeep, International Harvester, Avanti, and Checker companies were the remaining North American auto manufacturers.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy believed that American Motors's reputation of building reliable, economical cars could translate into a new strategy that could follow AMC buyers as they traded into larger, more expensive vehicles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors, in reality, had produced large cars throughout its history.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler Ambassadors were as large as a full-sized Ford or Chevy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] There was only an absence of largest-sized cars from the American Motors lineup in 1963 and 1964 The first cars bearing his signature were the 1965 models.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1965 models were a major makeover of the new platform that had just been introduced in 1963.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] These were a longer Ambassador series and new convertibles for the larger models.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] During mid-year, a fastback, called the Marlin, was added.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] It competed directly with cars like the Dodge Charger, but AMC's "family-sized" fastback emphasized personal-luxury.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The continuing quest "in the business world's toughest race – the grinding contest against the Big Three automobile makers" also meant annual styling changes requiring large expenditures.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors's management total confidence "that the new 1965 models would stem a bothersome decline" actually began falling behind in share of sales.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Moreover, a new line of redesigned cars in the full and mid-sized markets was launched in the fall of 1966.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The cars won acclaim for their fluid styling, and Abernethy's ideas did work as Ambassador sales increased significantly.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, the dated designs of the Rambler Americans hurt its sales, which offset gains from Ambassador sales.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] There were quality control problems with introducing the new full-sized cars and persistent rumors of the company's demise because of its precarious cash flow.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Consumer Reports' negative ratings for American Motors' safety did not help.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] During this time, AMC's international sales were expanding.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] From only 18,000 cars five years ago, the 1965 model year AMC sold 74,420 vehicles in Canada, Europe, and Latin America.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC remained the most significant U.S. seller of autos in both France and Germany.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy also called for the de-emphasis of the Rambler brand because he believed the public associated it too strongly with economy cars and that it was hindering the sale of American Motors' other models at a time when mid and luxury car sales were robust.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, he ordered that for 1966, the Ambassador and Marlin were to be badged purely as a product of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The strategy shift at first seemed to be working because sales of the redesigned 1965 and 1966 Ambassadors improved, even as AMC's overall production decreased from the record level achieved in 1963.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, corporate earnings per share were a meager 27 cents per share, the lowest since AMC made its famous compact car comeback in 1958.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Investors received a message of the changing fortune of the automaker when the company's 1966 annual financial report was delivered in a plain brown wrapper, instead of the previous year's glossy cover.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] A completely new design was also slated for the larger 1967 models.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This strategy added $60 million in retooling costs, a significant stretch for the company.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The latest models shared fewer parts and were more expensive to build.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Abernethy continued his objective to position the new Rebel and Ambassador designs on an equal basis with competitive economy models marketed by the Big Three.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors did not have their own electric car program as did the Big Three, and after some negotiation, a contract was drawn in 1967 with Gulton Industries to develop a new battery based on lithium and a speed controller designed by Victor Wouk.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] A nickel-cadmium battery powered 1969 Rambler station wagon demonstrated the power systems that according to the scientist was a "wonderful car".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was also the start of other "plug-in"-type experimental American Motors vehicles developed with Gulton – the Amitron city concept car and later the similar Electron.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although the new models were well received by the motor industry media, the last quarter sales for AMC ended September 30, 1966 (AMC was not on a calendar fiscal year) were disappointing.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company recorded a balance sheet loss of $12,648,000 for the year before Tax Credits and deferred Tax Assets.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time the board had lost confidence in Abernethy due to his vast spending which had unstabilized the company and each year under his leadership the company had suffered substantial financial losses.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] As a result, Abernethy was forced into taking an "early retirement" from American Motors on January 9, 1967.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin quickly instituted changes to American Motors's offerings and tried to regain market share by focusing on younger demographic markets.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chapin's first decision was to cut the price of the Rambler to within $200 of the basic Volkswagen Beetle.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Innovative marketing ideas included making air conditioning standard on all 1968 Ambassador models (available as a delete option).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This made American Motors the first U.S. automaker to make air conditioning standard equipment on a line of cars, preceding even luxury makes such as Lincoln, Imperial, and Cadillac.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The company introduced exciting entries for the decade's muscle car boom, most notably the AMX.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, the Javelin served as the company's entrant into the sporty pony car market created by the Plymouth Barracuda and the Ford Mustang.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Additional operating cash was derived in 1968 through the sale of Kelvinator Appliance, once one of the firm's core operating units.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Kelvinator divestiture left American Motors a downsized company solely manufacturing automobiles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler marque was discontinued for the larger 1968 domestic models, leaving only the small Rambler American as the last product to bear the name through 1969.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Rambler brand continued to be used only for export markets, with Mexico being the last market to use it in 1983.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, American Motors was the brand used for all American Motors passenger cars, and all vehicles from that date bore the American Motors name and the new corporate logo.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "American Motors" and "AMC" were used interchangeably in corporate literature well into the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The branding issue was further complicated when the company's Eagle all-wheel drive passenger cars were marketed as the American Eagle in the 1980s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In the late 1960s, Kaiser Industries Corporation decided to leave the automotive industry and sought a buyer for its money-losing Kaiser Jeep division.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' vice president for manufacturing, Gerald C.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers, headed the team sent to evaluate Kaiser's Jeep factories.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although opposed by AMC's top management, Chapin made a significant decision in February 1970 to purchase Kaiser Jeep for $70 million.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Although it was a gamble, Chapin believed Jeep vehicles would complement American Motors' passenger car business.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] (The latter being the only Nissan-branded vehicle in the United States until the 1980s when the Datsun name was phased out in favor of Nissan.) Jeep by far had the largest market share of the 4x4 market during this time.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors gained the iconic Jeep brand of light trucks and SUVs, as well as Kaiser-Jeep's government contracts – notably the M151 line of military Jeeps and the DJ-Series postal Jeeps.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors also expanded its international network.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The military and special products business was reconstituted as "American Motors General Products Division", later reorganized as AM General.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1970, American Motors consolidated all passenger cars under one distinct brand identity and debuted the Hornet range of compact cars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet and the later Gremlin shared platforms.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Gremlin, the first North American-built subcompact, sold more than 670,000 units from 1970 through 1978.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet became American Motors' best-selling passenger car since the Rambler Classic, with more than 860,000 units sold when production ended in 1977.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Hornet platform continued to be built under various models through 1987.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] For a time, both the Hornet and Gremlin could be ordered with Levi's denim interiors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors supplied Mark VII Limited owner Jack Webb with two Matadors, a sedan and a wagon, for use in his popular television series *Adam-12*, increasing the cars' public profile.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matadors saw fleet use as taxis, government, police, and fire vehicles in some states.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1973, American Motors signed a licensing agreement with Curtiss-Wright to build Wankel engines for cars and Jeeps.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting in 1974, the Matador sedan and station wagon were mildly refreshed, with new boxier front and rear ends, making it full-sized.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This second-generation model was produced virtually unchanged until 1978.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sagging sales and tight finances resulted in the discontinuation of the Matador line after the 1978 model leaving American Motors to focus almost exclusively on its Hornet platform-based cars and the Jeep line.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] From 1970, the Rebel and Ambassador were identical from the A-pillar back.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador continued as AMC's upmarket model with higher trim, more equipment, and air conditioning as standard.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] From the A-pillar forward, the Ambassador was redesigned and stretched 7 inches (178 mm) to become the biggest ever, just as the 1973 Arab Oil Embargo sparked gasoline rationing across the nation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The additional length was due to a new front-end design and more substantial energy-absorbing bumpers required of all automobiles sold in the U.S.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales of all large cars fell due to economic problems and rising gasoline prices.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Ambassador became a full-sized car in 1974 and was discontinued after the 1974 model year, leaving only the Matador as American Motors' full-size offering.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Nash and American Motors made Ambassadors from 1927 through 1974, the longest use of the same model name for any American Motors product and, at the time, the longest continuously used nameplate in the industry.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, the first-generation Matador two-door hardtop, known as the "flying brick" due to its poor aerodynamics in NASCAR competition, was replaced with a sleek, smoothly shaped, and radically styled two-door coupe.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The model received praise for its design, including "Best Styled Car of 1974" by *Car and Driver* magazine, customer satisfaction, and sold almost 100,000 coupes over five years.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador Coupe shared few components with the Matador sedan and station wagon other than suspension, drive train, some trim, and interior parts.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1974, American Motors's AM General subsidiary began building urban transit buses in cooperation with Flyer Industries of Winnipeg, Manitoba.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] A total of 5,431 *Metropolitan* buses, including 219 electric trolley buses, were built before production ceased in 1979.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of diesel buses had ceased in 1978, with only trolley bus production taking place in 1979.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer, an innovative all-new model introduced in March 1975 and marketed as "the first wide small car", was a subcompact designed to provide the comfort of a full-sized car.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Its pre-production development coincided with tightened U.S. federal passenger emissions and auto safety regulations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer sold well its first two years with 262,772 combined units sold in the US.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] With the Arab Oil Embargo of 1973, General Motors aborted the Wankel rotary engine around which the Pacer had been designed, as its fuel consumption exceeded that of conventional engines with similar power.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Therefore, American Motors's existing 258 and 232 cu in (4.2 and 3.8 L) AMC Straight-6 engines were used in the Pacer instead.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The fuel economy was better than the expected rotary engine's, but the I6's gas mileage was relatively low in light of the new focus on energy efficiency.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Also, as the Pacer shared few components other than the drivetrain with other American Motors cars, it was expensive to make, and the cost increased when sales fell steeply after the first two years.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Pacer line was discontinued in mid-1980.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, "AMC used cars, as far back as 1967, had the advantage of good warranty coverage ... so most owners were conscious of low-cost car maintenance ...
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC units became some of the very best buys on the used car market" by 1975.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 1977 Gremlin had redesigned headlights, grille, rear hatch, and fascia.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] For economy in the fuel crisis, American Motors offered the car with a more fuel-efficient Volkswagen-designed Audi 4-cylinder engine 2.0 L (122 cu in).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The engine was expensive for American Motors to build, and the Gremlin retained the less costly but less economical 232 cu in (3.8 L) as standard equipment.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was a sporty appearance package on the Hornet hatchback featuring upgrades, as well as the 258 cu in (4.2 L) inline six as standard with a choice of three-speed automatic or four-speed manual transmissions.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was optional with the automatic transmission.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] As all Matadors now received standard equipment that was formerly optional (e.g., power steering, automatic transmission), the "Brougham" package was dropped from 1977.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Optional on the Matador coupe was a landau vinyl roof with opera windows, and top-line Barcelonas offered new two-tone paint.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1978 model year, the Hornet platform was redesigned with an adaptation of the new Gremlin front-end design and renamed AMC Concord.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors targeted it at the emerging "premium compact" market segment, paying particular attention to ride and handling, standard equipment, trim, and interior luxury.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gremlins borrowed the Concord instrument panel, a Hornet AMX-inspired GT sports appearance package, and a new striping treatment for X models.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC Pacer hood was modified to clear a V8 engine, and a Sports package replaced the former X package.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] With falling sales of Matador Coupes, sedans, and wagons, their 304 cu in (5.0 L) V8 engine was dropped, leaving only the 258 cu in (4.2 L) Inline-6 (standard on coupes and sedans) and the 360 cu in (5.9 L) V8 (optional on coupes and sedans, standard on wagons).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The two-tone Barcelona luxury package was offered on Matador sedans, and two-tone red paint was introduced as an additional Barcelona option.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Matador production ceased at the end of the model year with total sales of 10,576 units.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Matador was no longer attractive as automakers struggled to overcome economic woes, including continuing fuel price increases and double-digit U.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the 1979 model year, the Spirit sedan replaced the Gremlin.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] A new fastback version of the car, the Spirit Liftback, proved successful.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December, Pacer production ceased after a small run of 1980 models was built to use up parts stock.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concords received a new front-end treatment, and in their final season, hatchbacks became available in DL trim.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Concord and Spirit models were dropped after 1983.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, Time noted record Jeep sales and a backlog of orders for AM General's buses.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In July 1977, it was announced that the General Services Administration of the Federal U.S. government had awarded AMC a three-year contract worth $15 million to lease 5,838 cars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Since the beginning of the fiscal year on October 1, 1976, the GSA had purchased 8,700 cars from AMC for $30 million.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] On October 21, 1977, Roy Chapin Jr. retired, and Gerald C.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] On March 31, 1978, American Motors and Renault announced a sweeping agreement for jointly manufacturing and distributing cars and trucks that would benefit both.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] A month later, American Motors announced that it would halt the production of standard urban transit buses after about 4,300 were sold by its AM General subsidiary over a period of three years.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Environmental Protection Agency ordered the recall of all American Motors's 1976 cars (except those conforming to California emissions regulations) – some 270,000 vehicles— plus 40,000 1975 and 1976 Jeeps and mini trucks, for correction of a fault in the pollution control system.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Total cost was estimated at up to $3 million, or more than AMC had earned the previous quarter.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors lost an estimated $65 million on its conventional (non-Jeep) cars for the fiscal year that ended September 30, 1978, but strong Jeep sales helped the company to an overall $36.7 million profit on sales of $2.6 billion.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] However, American Motors faced costly engineering work to bring their Jeeps into compliance with a federal directive for all 4-wheel-drive vehicles to average 15 mpg‑US (16 L/100 km; 18 mpg‑imp) by 1981.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In December 1978 the government of Iran, embroiled in the Iranian revolution, cut off oil exports to the world.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This caused a devastating effect on all American automobile makers and American consumers.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Gasoline prices jumped 52 percent between September and December 1979.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Each of the Big Three (Ford, General Motors, Chrysler) lost money throughout 1979 leading to Chrysler becoming insolvent and considering bankruptcy by September.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Ford survived only because of its European operations, eventually losing $7 billion in domestic sales from 1979 to 1982.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] During the crisis, and with its domestic market share at 1.83%, American Motors struck a deal with Renault, the nationally owned French automaker in October 1979.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC would receive a $150 million cash injection, $50 million in credits, and also the rights to start building the Renault 5 in 1982 (a deal for Renault products to be sold through the American Motors-Jeep dealer network had already been made in 1979).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In return, Renault acquired a 22.5% interest in American Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This was not the first time the two companies had worked together.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking a prestige model line in the early 1960s, Renault assembled CKD kits and marketed Rambler cars in France.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] A drop in Jeep sales caused by the declining economy and soaring energy prices began to constrict American Motors' cash flow.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] At the same time, pressure increased on the company's non-Jeep product lines.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The face-lifts and rebranding of American Motors' once-innovative and successful cars were not enough in a competitive landscape that had changed dramatically.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] No longer was the threat limited to the Big Three automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In response to the 1979 oil crisis, the Big Three had resorted to importing foreign motor vehicles, mainly Japanese models.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Japanese models were mass-marketed and had lower manufacturing costs.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] By the end of 1980 Japanese manufacturers surpassed Detroit's production totals, becoming first in the world.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Indeed, the share of Japanese cars in U.S. auto purchases rose from 9 percent in 1976 to 21 percent in 1980.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Japanese manufacturers (Honda, Toyota, and Nissan) used streamlined production methods such as outsourcing and Just In Time (JIT) supply-chain management.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] They had new, highly efficient assembly plants in the United States.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] And now they targeted the heart of American Motors' passenger product line: small cars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In early 1980, the banks refused American Motors further credit.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Lacking both capital and resources for the new, truly modern products it needed to offer, the company turned to Renault for a $90 million loan (US$351,676,090 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] By September that year, American Motors's U.S. market share had fallen to 1.7%, and in November sales dropped 19.1%.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors warned stockholders that the company could be bankrupted if they did not approve a plan for Renault to acquire as much as 59% of the company.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] On December 16, 1980, American Motors shareholders "overwhelmingly approved making the French Government-owned Renault" their company's principal owner.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Jean-Marc Lepeu, former corporate treasurer at Renault, became vice president for finance at American Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In September 1981, Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault veteran of 23 years, mainly in manufacturing, became American Motors' executive vice president for manufacturing.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In January 1982, the company's president W.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Meyers as chairman and CEO, and Dedeurwaerder moved up to be president.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] By this time Renault owned 46% of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Dedeurwaerder brought a broad perspective at this critical time: he is credited with streamlining many of American Motors' arcane management techniques.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] He also instituted important improvements in plant layouts, as well as in cost and quality control.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Having increased its stake in the company several times to keep it solvent, Renault eventually owned 49% in 1983.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Some view this development as ending American Motors' run as a truly American car company.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] New ownership and management heralded a new product venture for American Motors: a line of modern front-wheel drive cars, designed by Renault, to be produced at Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1980, all American Motors cars received a new rust-proofing process using Ziebart as Factory Rust Protection.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The extra protection also included aluminized trim screws, plastic inner fender liners, and galvanized steel in every exterior body panel, along with the unibody getting a deep-dip (up to the window line) bath in epoxy-based primer.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In August 1979, for the 1980 model year, American Motors introduced four-wheel-drive versions of the Spirit and Concord, calling the collective line the AMC Eagle.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles rapidly became one of the company's best-known products and are considered one of the first "crossover SUVs".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Eagles used the 2-wheel drive body shells mounted on an all-new platform developed by American Motors in the late 1970s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Featuring an innovative full-time four-wheel-drive system, it sold best in snow-prone areas.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Sales started strongly but declined over time.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] While the two-wheel drive Spirit and Concord were discontinued after 1983 as the company concentrated on its new Renault Alliance, the Eagle survived for five years longer, albeit only in station wagon form, into the 1988 model year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This meant the four-wheel-drive Eagle was the lone representative of the American Motors brand from 1984 until the 1988 model year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] All the company's remaining output was branded Renault or Jeep.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The last AMC Eagle was built on December 14, 1987.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Renault Alliance was the first joint product of the American Motors-Renault partnership.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Introduced in 1983, the Alliance was a front-wheel-drive Renault 9 compact car slightly restyled for the American market by Dick Teague, mainly to comply with American safety standards, and produced by American Motors at Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The car was badged as a Renault, and some cars also carried American Motors badges.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] It was available as a sedan with two or four doors and later as a convertible.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The hatchback, introduced in 1984 and badged as the Renault Encore, was the same as the European Renault 11 model.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new model, introduced during increased interest in small cars, won several awards, including Motor Trend Car of the Year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] *Motor Trend* declared: "The Alliance may well be the best-assembled first-year car we've ever seen.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Way to go Renault!" The Alliance was listed as number one on *Car and Driver's* list of ten best cars for 1983.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The positive reception and sales of 200,000 Alliances by 1984 was hindered by the availability of only two body styles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Alliance was a European-designed car that was not fully suited to U.S. market demands.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The distribution network was also not well supported, which led to the lower quality delivered by dealerships with "disastrous consequences" for the image of the automobiles and high warranty costs because of quality failings, which greatly impacted sales from 1985 to the end of production in 1987.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] After the 1983 model year, American Motors focused entirely on four-wheel drive autos; the company stopped producing rear-wheel-drive cars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors facilities were then used to assemble the Renault-branded Alliance and Encore compact and subcompact cars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] For the final 1987 model year, a higher-performance version of the Alliance 2-door sedan and the convertible was sold as the Renault GTA.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] This version had a Renault two-liter engine that was exclusive to it and not shared with the European Renault 9 and 11 models.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Encore models were renamed Alliance Hatchback in 1987.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Alliance and GTA production ended in June of that year, while the Renault 9 and 11 models continued through the 1988 model year in Europe, being replaced by the all-new Renault 19.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] More beneficial to American Motors' future was the introduction of an all-new line of compact Jeep Cherokee and Wagoneer models in the autumn of 1983 for the 1984 model year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault's François Castaing, head of AMC's product development team, designed the new Jeep platform with styling by Dick Teague.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Renault was interested in selling the Cherokee in Europe, but the vehicle needed to be lighter and more fuel-efficient to meet European expectations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The new XJ weighed 3,100 pounds (1,406 kilograms), due to its unibody construction and lighter components such as the front seats taken from the Renault 9 and 11 and new Renault Alliance.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] AMC's initial forecasts of 40,000 Cherokee and Wagoneer sales were shattered, with sales amounting to 75,000 in their first year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The three leading off-roading magazines, *Petersen's 4-Wheel & Off-Road*, *Four Wheeler*, and *Off-Road* each named the new Jeep Cherokee as the "4x4 of the year." The popularity of these downsized Jeeps pioneered a new market segment for what later became defined as the sport utility vehicle (SUV).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] They initially used the AMC 150.4 cu in (2.5 L) OHV four-cylinder engine with a carburetor, and a General Motors-built 2.8 L (171 cu in) carbureted V6 was optional.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] In 1986, throttle-body injection replaced the carburetor on the 2.5 L I4 engines.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] A Renault 2.1 L (128 cu in) Turbo-Diesel I4 diesel was also offered.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Starting with the 1987 models, a new 4.0 L (244 cu in) I6 engine, derived from the older 258 cu in (4.23 L) I6 with a new head design and an electronic fuel injection system, replaced the outsourced V6.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] American Motors' "new" engine was designed with help from Renault and incorporated Renault-Bendix (Renix) parts for fuel and ignition management.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The 4.0 developed an outstanding reputation for reliability and toughness.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Retained by Chrysler after the buyout, the design received continuous improvements and refinements until its discontinuation at the end of the 2006 model year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The AMC 4.0 engine saw extensive application in XJ Cherokees and Wagoneers, Grand Cherokees, and Wranglers, and many of those engines saw (or are seeing) extremely long lives, quite a few exceeding 300,000 mi (480,000 km).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Chrysler built the XJ Cherokee until the end of the 2001 model year in the U.S. and until 2005 in China.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Unlike most sport-utility vehicles based on adapted pickup truck designs, the Cherokee XJ SUV came first, and the Comanche was designed as a later pickup truck version.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] Production of the full-sized pickups ceased after 1987.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p01] The Grand Wagoneer and 360 V8 engine were dropped after 1991 (the last American-made vehicle whose engine used a carburetor for fuel delivery), and the Comanche was discontinued after 1992.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Significant changes occurred in 1985 as the market moved away from American Motors' small models.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] With fuel relatively cheap again, buyers turned to larger, more powerful automobiles, and American Motors was unprepared for this development.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even the venerable Jeep CJ-5 was dropped after a *60 Minutes* TV news magazine staged exposé of rollover tendencies under extreme conditions.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors also confronted an angry workforce.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Labor was taking revenge, and reports circulated about the sabotage of vehicles on the assembly lines because of the failure to receive promised wage increases.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] There were rumors that the aging Kenosha plant was to be shut down.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the same time, Chrysler was having trouble meeting the demand for its M-body rear-drive models (Dodge Diplomat, Plymouth Gran Fury, and Chrysler Fifth Avenue).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Because they were assembled using the old "gate and buck system" and the tooling could be easily moved, Chrysler could supply the components and control the quality while AMC assembled the car.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy agreed to use some of AMC's idle plant capacity in Kenosha.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1985, Renault's chairman in France, Bernard Hanon, was dismissed by the government in a shake-up triggered by huge losses as a result of his goal to revolutionize Renault's product strategy in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was instrumental in 1981 for the company to invest in AMC and also made Renault a full-line automaker, but this ballooned the firm's debt.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault relinquished its number one sales position in Europe, which it held from 1980 until 1983.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company had been losing money since 1981 and had fallen to sixth place behind Ford, Fiat, Volkswagen, Peugeot, and General Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Strikes plagued Renault at the end of 1984, and the French government introduced price controls that severely cut the profit margins on cars sold in France, Renault's most important market.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Hanon was replaced by Georges Besse, ex-president of Produits Chimiques Ugine Kuhlmann in France.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Paul Tippett resigned to become president of a textile company.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Dedeurwaerder, president since 1982 and chief executive officer since September 1984, announced at the Paris Auto Show in October 1985, that AMC would begin imports of the innovative seven-seat, front-wheel-drive Espace minivan in the spring of 1986.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] This was part of expanding the range of Renault models that include plans for marketing the Renault Alpine GTA/A510 sports car through select AMC dealers.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In December 1985, Dedeurwaerder became chairman of AMC's executive committee while continuing as the company's president and CEO.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Joe Cappy was moved up from executive vice president to chief operating officer, and Tippet's position was filled by an ex-Renault vice president, Pierre Semerena.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Semerena made his managerial reputation as a no-nonsense cost cutter.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The new management responded with tactical moves by selling the lawn care Wheel Horse Products Division and signing an agreement to build Jeeps in the People's Republic of China.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Pentagon had problems with AM General, a significant defense contractor, being managed by a partially French-government-owned firm.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The U.S. government would not allow a foreign government to own a substantial portion of an important defense supplier.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] As a result, the profitable AM General Division was sold to LTV Corporation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another milestone within AMC's management was the departure of Dick Teague.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] He was American Motors' design vice president for 23 years - an industry record. he was responsible for many Jeep and AMC designs, including the Javelin, AMX, Hornet, Gremlin, Pacer, Matador coupe, and the Cherokee XJ.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In France, Renault continued to experience financial trouble.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The investment in American Motors (including the construction of a new Canadian assembly plant in Brampton, Ontario) forced cuts at home, resulting in the closure of several French plants and mass layoffs.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, Jeep vehicles were riding an unprecedented surge in demand.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] It seemed to Besse and others that American Motors was on course for profitability.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, on November 17, 1986, Besse, who had a high-profile among French capitalists, was assassinated by a member of a French clandestine far-left extremist group, Action Directe.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] AMC's plans to reinvigorate sales with higher-priced Renaults continued for a little longer, with the plan being a three-pronged lineup beginning with the mid-sized Medallion, the larger Premier above it, and the sporty Renault Alpine providing a halo car.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Medallion and the Premier both went on sale, but Alpine never made its planned mid-1987 rollout.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under pressure from Renault executives following Besse's death, Renault's new president, Raymond Levy, set out to repair employee relations and divest the company of its investment in American Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault owned 46.1% of American Motors' outstanding shares of stock.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1986, American Motors posted a $91.3 million loss.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The earlier agreement between Chrysler and American Motors in 1985, under which American Motors would produce M-body chassis rear-drive large cars for five years from mid-1986 through 1990, fed the rumor that Chrysler was about to buy AMC.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to the head of manufacturing for Chrysler, Stephan Sharf, the existing relationship with AMC producing a car for a competitor facilitated the negotiations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 9, 1987, Chrysler agreed to buy Renault's share in American Motors, plus all the remaining shares, for about $1.5 billion ($4,250,878,735 in 2025 dollars).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler made no secret that they were only interested in AMC for Jeep, AMC's new assembly plant in Canada, and AMC's network of 1,300 dealerships nationwide.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] With the sale complete, American Motors became the Jeep-Eagle division of Chrysler on August 25, 1988, and was fully merged as of March 29, 1990.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The sale came at a time when the automotive press was enthusiastic about the proposed 1988 lineup of Renault, Eagle, and Jeep vehicles and reported that the small automaker's financial outlook was improving.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' quarterly results for all of 1987 were positive.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler purchased American Motors when the company appeared to be in an excellent financial position with its new product line.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] It was the Jeep brand that Chrysler CEO Lee Iacocca wanted – in particular, the ZJ Gen. of the Grand Cherokee, then under development by Jeep engineers, which ultimately proved highly profitable for Chrysler (the nameplate remains in production today).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the buyout included other attractive deal sweeteners for Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among them was the world-class, brand-new manufacturing plant in Bramalea, Ontario, which offered Iacocca an unprecedented opportunity to increase his company's production capacity at a fire-sale price.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors had designed and built the plant in anticipation of building the Renault 25-based Eagle Premier.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault left the U.S. market entirely as a brand in 1987.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Thus, the Renault Medallion was sold through the new Jeep-Eagle division as an Eagle, not a Renault.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep-Eagle division was formed from the American Motors Jeep Renault dealer network.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep and Eagle vehicles were marketed primarily by former American Motors dealers.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors badge was last used on the Eagle Sports Wagon through the 1988 model year, then eliminated, and the Eagle car brand was phased out by 1998.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 1954 merger of Nash-Kelvinator Corporation and Hudson Motor Car Company that established American Motors was led by Nash-Kelvinator president George W.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason to reap benefits from the strengths of the two firms to battle the much larger "Big Three" automakers (General Motors, Ford, and Chrysler).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The merger was initially intended to be three-way, with Packard being the number three.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason had first discussed the possibility of a merger with Packard president James J.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Nance insisted that if Packard were to join, he would have to be the CEO of the new company.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason fully intended to lead the new company, thus the deal did not go through.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Packard acquired Studebaker two months after Nash acquired Hudson.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason became CEO and president of the new company, and Hudson's president A.E.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Barit retired to become an American Motors board member.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason selected long-time Nash associate and future governor of Michigan, George W.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Roy Abernethy, ex-vice president of sales for Willys, was hired to be vice president of sales.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Following Mason's sudden death on October 8, 1954, Romney took over, reorganizing the company and focusing American Motors' future on a new small car line.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Mason's death also allowed Romney to put an end to any further discussions for a merger between American Motors and Studebaker-Packard.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] By the end of 1957, the legacy Nash and Hudson brands were completely phased out and replaced with the Rambler and Metropolitan brands.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company struggled initially, but Rambler's sales took off under Romney.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] A Rambler won the 1959 Mobil Economy Run, and by 1960, was the third-most-popular brand of automobile in the United States, behind Ford and Chevrolet.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] George Romney left American Motors in 1962 to run for governor in Michigan and was replaced as CEO by Roy Abernethy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Abernethy had been with AMC since the 1954 merger and as vice president of sales was responsible for successfully building AMC's sales and distribution network during the 1950s and early 1960s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] After two model years (1963 and 1964) of only producing compact cars, Abernethy shifted the focus of American Motors back to bigger and more profitable cars such as the Ambassador line and tried to move away from the perceived negative of the Rambler's economy car image.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, the enormous costs of developing the new cars and engines meant American Motors now had problems in securing working capital to keep the company going.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors sales dropped 20% in the first half of 1966, and the firm reported a fiscal six-month loss of $4.2 million on sales of $479 million.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Evans invested more than $2 million because American Motors's stock was selling for only 60% of the company's net worth; thus, he became its largest stockholder and was named its chairman on June 6, 1966, replacing Richard E.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cross, who continued as a director and chairman of the executive committee.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the quarter ending September 30, 1966, American Motors recorded a loss of $12,648,000 before tax credits and deferred tax assets.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In the face of deteriorating financial and market positions, Abernethy "retired" as CEO in 1967, and Evans "resigned" as chairman.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., the son of Hudson co-founder Roy D.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' public explanation for the removals was that the two had "stepped aside according to a plan to give a younger team an opportunity to move the company forward".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin took charge of revitalizing the company, and designer Dick Teague economized by developing several vehicles from common stampings.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The AMC Matador was in reality a facelift of the AMC Rebel, itself derived from the 1967 AMC Ambassador platform.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] While prices and costs were cut, Teague designed new and more sporty automobiles resulting in the Javelin and AMX muscle cars; and the AMC Hornet.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] From 1970 Jeep production complemented AMC's existing passenger-car business.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Chapin's leadership, AMC produced all-new compact car designs based on the Hornet platform including the Gremlin and Concord.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers replaced the retiring William Luneburg as president and Chief Operating Officer.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Only 5 months later, upon the retirement of Chapin, Meyers became chairman and CEO on October 21, 1977.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Meyers was 49 years old, and became the youngest top executive in the automobile industry.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers abandoned AMC's policy of head-on competition and instead focused on revamping its four-wheel drive vehicles, a market segment left untended by the large automakers, and by acquiring advanced technology.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyer's began talks with Renault in 1979 and from 1980, American Motors partnered with the French automaker to help finance their manufacturing operations, obtain much-needed capital, and source subcompact vehicles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] On December 16, 1980, Renault became the principal owner of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] At age 53, Meyers retired from the company in February 1982.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] By that time, Renault controlled 46% of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Meyers was succeeded as chairman by former American Motors president W.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, Tippett was a member of American Motors management for only three years but had overseen almost all vehicle-making operations during his time as president.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Jose Dedeurwaerder, a Renault manager, replaced Tippet as president.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Tippet's tenure as CEO was short-lived and in September 1984, he was replaced by Dedeurwaerder.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] On September 28, 1984, Dedeurwaerder was promoted to CEO, with Tippett remaining on as chairman.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] On February 25, 1985, AMC announced its first full-year profit since 1979.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The success was short-lived as on July 31, 1985, AMC announced that it had received a $50 million loan from Renault following a second-quarter loss of $70.4 million.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Under Dedeurwaerder, Chrysler entered an agreement with American Motors in 1985 to produce Dodge Diplomats and Plymouth Furys, as well as Dodge Omnis and Plymouth Horizons in American Motors' Kenosha, Wisconsin, plant.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] At the time, American Motors had excess manufacturing capacity.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In January 1986, Dedeurwaerder was named Renault's executive vice president of worldwide sales and marketing.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] He remained president and CEO, and chairman of the executive committee at AMC until March 23, 1986, when he was succeeded in the former two roles by Joseph E.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] By 1986, Renault had lost $700 million on $22 billion of sales in the U.S. market, and was $9 billion in debt.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] On March 23, 1986, former executive vice president of operations Joseph E.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Cappy was named president and chief executive officer of American Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler acquired American Motors in August 1987.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The primary task of Chrysler management was to integrate the two companies as quickly as possible.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' final CEO, was tasked with achieving this by Chrysler president Gerald Greenwald.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] After the buyout Cappy joined Chrysler as group vice president of the new Jeep-Eagle division.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 1989, he was named Chrysler's vice president of brand development.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The following year he became Chrysler's vice president of international operations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was forced to constantly innovate for 33 years until Chrysler absorbed it in 1987.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The lessons learned from this experience were integrated into the company that bought American Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The organization, strategies, and several key executives allowed Chrysler to gain an edge over the competition.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even today, the lessons gained from the American Motors experience continue to benefit other firms in the industry.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] There are many legacies of American Motors's business strategies.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors could formulate strategies that industry critics often evaluated as "strokes of brilliance".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr., American Motors realized they were up against the giants of the industry, so to compete successfully they had to be able to move quickly and with ingenuity.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] An essential strategy practiced by American Motors was to rely on outside vendors to supply components in which they had differential advantages.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] This approach was finally accepted within the U.S. auto industry, but only after each of the Big Three experienced the failure of attempting to be self-sufficient.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Another example of American Motors' agility was the ability of management to squeeze money out of reluctant bankers, even in the face of bankruptcy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] These core abilities helped save the company from collapse and, after each obstacle, gave it the wherewithal to keep it operating.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Ironically, American Motors was never stronger than just before its demise.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' managers anticipated important trends in the automotive industry.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] It preached fuel efficiency in the 1950s, long before most auto buyers demanded it.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Led by American Motors' Rambler and several European cars, the small car innovation reduced the Big Three's market share from 93% in 1957 to 82% in 1959.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The company inherited foreign manufacturing and sales partnerships from Nash and continued developing business relations, decades before most of the international consolidations among automobile makers took place.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was the first U.S. automaker to establish an ownership agreement with a foreign automaker, Renault.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although small in size, American Motors was able to introduce numerous industry innovations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Starting in 1957, American Motors was the only U.S. manufacturer to fully immerse all automobile bodies in primer paint for protection against rust, until competitors adopted the practice in 1964.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Even one of American Motors's most expensive new product investments (the Pacer) established many features that were later adopted by the auto industry worldwide.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] These included aerodynamic body design, space-efficient interiors, aircraft-style doors, and a large greenhouse for visibility.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors was also effective in other areas, such as marketing, by introducing low-rate financing.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' four-wheel-drive vehicles established the foundation for the modern SUV market segments, and "classic" Jeep models remain the benchmark in this field.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin drew on his experiences as a hunter and fisherman and marketed the Jeep brand successfully to people with like interests.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The brand developed a cult appeal that continues.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase of American Motors was instrumental in reviving Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Robert Lutz, former president of Chrysler, the American Motors acquisition was a big and risky undertaking.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The purchase was part of Chrysler's strategic "retreat-cum-diversification" plan that he states did not have the proper focus.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Initially, the goal was to obtain the world-renowned Jeep brand.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] However, Lutz discovered that the decision to buy American Motors turned out to be a gold mine for Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] At that time, Chrysler's management was attempting to find a model to improve structure and operations, *"something that would help get our minds unstuck and thinking beyond the old paradigms that we were so familiar with*".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this transformation, *"Chrysler's acquisition of AMC was one of the all-time great moments in corporate serendipity*" according to Lutz *" that most definitely played a key role in demonstrating how to accomplish change*".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] According to Lutz (1993), while American Motors had its share of problems, it was far from being a bunch of "brain-dead losers".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] He describes the "troops" at American Motors as more like the Wake Island Marines in battle, "with almost no resources, and fighting a vastly superior enemy, they were able to roll out an impressive succession of new products".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] After first reacting with anger to the purchase, Chrysler managers soon anticipated the benefits.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] To further solidify the organizational competencies held by American Motors, Lee Iacocca agreed to retain former American Motors units, such as engineering, completely intact.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In addition, American Motors' lead engineer, François Castaing, was made head of all engineering at Chrysler.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In an unthinkable strategic move, Castaing completely dismantled the entrenched Chrysler groups.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In their place, American Motors's "platform team" was implemented.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] These were close-knit cross-functional groups responsible for the whole vehicle, contrasted with Chrysler's highly functional structure.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In this capacity, Castaing's strategy was to eliminate the corporate administrative overhead bureaucracy.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] This move shifted corporate culture and agitated veteran executives who believed that Chrysler's reputation as "the engineering company" was being destroyed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Yet, according to the popular press, by the 1980s, Chrysler's reputation was shot, and in Lutz's view, only dramatic action would change that.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In summary, Chrysler's purchase of American Motors laid the critical foundation to help re-establish a strategy for its revival in the 1990s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Top managers at Chrysler after the AMC buyout appeared to have made errors similar to those by American Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] For example, Chrysler invested heavily in new untested models while not keeping up its profitable high-volume lines.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The American Motors influence also continued at General Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM recruited a new executive team to turn itself from near bankruptcy in the early 2000s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Among the new strategists at GM was Lutz, who understood the importance of passion in product design.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Lutz's new thinking at GM incorporated the systems and structures that originated from American Motors's lean and focused operations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Renault implemented the lessons it learned from its investment in American Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The French firm took a parallel approach as it did with its initial ownership of American Motors and applied it to resurrect the money-losing Nissan automaker in Japan.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In 2009, in a deal brokered by the Obama administration, Italian automaker Fiat initiated a white knight takeover of Chrysler to save the struggling automaker from liquidation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The two firms would later fully merge to create Fiat Chrysler Automobiles in 2014, and would further merge with the French firm PSA Group, owners of the Citroën and Peugeot brands, to form Stellantis in 2021.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler revived the "Spirit" name, which was discontinued by AMC after 1983 for use on one of its A platform cars (the Dodge Spirit) from 1989 until 1995.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The planned Renault Medallion was sold as the Eagle Medallion in 1988 and 1989.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The full-sized Premier's platform was far more advanced than anything Chrysler was building.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Plymouth almost received their rendition of the LH platform, which was to be called the Accolade.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Still, Chrysler decided to drop this version just before LH production started.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Chrysler 300M was likewise a Premier/LH-derived car and was initially to have been the next-generation Eagle Vision until the Eagle brand was dropped after 1998.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The LH Platform was subsequently re-engineered, using Mercedes-Benz components, into the Chrysler LX Platform, which was the basis for the Chrysler 300, Dodge Charger, and Dodge Challenger.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler's successor Stellantis later revived the Hornet name in 2023 for Dodge as a rebadged variant of the Alfa Romeo Tonale.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chrysler marketed the SJ Jeep Grand Wagoneer until 1991, leaving it almost entirely unaltered from the final American Motors rendition before the buyout.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Jeep Comanche pickup truck remained until 1992, while the Cherokee remained until 2001 in the United States.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The XJ Cherokee was produced in China through 2006 as the Cherokee 2500 (2.5L) and Cherokee 4000 (4.0L).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although it was not introduced until 1993, the Jeep Grand Cherokee was initially an American Motors-developed vehicle.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Traces of American Motors remained within.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' Toledo, Ohio, plants continued to manufacture the Jeep Wrangler and Liberty, as well as parts and components for Chrysler, Dodge, and Jeep vehicles (although Toledo Machining and Forge were closed in 2005).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although heavily downsized, American Motors' main plant in Wisconsin operated as the Kenosha Engine Plant, producing engines for several Chrysler Group products, including the Wrangler.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The plant was closed as part of the post-bailout restructuring of Chrysler in October 2010.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The 4.0 L (242 cu in) engine was used until the 2006 model year by DaimlerChrysler in the Jeep Wrangler.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] American Motors' technologically advanced Bramalea Assembly and Stamping Plants in Brampton, Ontario, later produced the LX-cars – the Chrysler 300, Dodge Challenger, Dodge Charger, and the now discontinued Dodge Magnum.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Both were retired when the Wrangler was completely redesigned for the 2007 model year.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General, sold by American Motors in 1983, is still in business building the American Motors-designed Humvee for American and allied militaries.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] AM General also built the now-discontinued civilian variant, the H1, and manufactured a Chevrolet Tahoe-derived companion, the H2, under contract to GM, who acquired the rights to the civilian Hummer brand in 1999.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] GM was forced to phase out the Hummer brand in early 2010 due to its bankruptcy restructuring after offering it for sale, but failing to find a suitable buyer.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Although Chrysler introduced new logos for its brands in the 1990s and again in 2010 after the Fiat Group took control of the company, Jeep still uses the American Motors-era logo introduced shortly after American Motors purchased the brand in 1970.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Until the Chrysler purchase, Jeep's logo also featured the American Motors emblem.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Beginning in 1960, American Motors' executive vice president of international operations Roy D.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin Jr. embarked on a strong international campaign to set up importation and local assembly operations of American Motors vehicles worldwide.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] In five years, Chapin increased foreign sales to 73,489 cars, which at the same time grew AMC's share of the U.S. export market from 2.5 percent to 14.3 percent.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] Chapin successfully established or re-established vehicle assembly operations in Argentina, Australia, Belgium (via Renault of France), Chile, Costa Rica, Germany, Iran, Mexico, New Zealand, Peru, Philippines, South Africa, and Venezuela.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] He also strengthened international export operations with exports to the United Kingdom, Denmark, Finland, Iceland, and Norway in Europe, and to countries in the Middle East, the Caribbean, and South America.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] The Rambler Classic would become the basis of Argentina's future national car, the Torino.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] After becoming CEO in 1967, Chapin organized the acquisition of Kaiser Jeep from Kaiser Industries in 1970, with American Motors, thereby inheriting all existing international Jeep operations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] These helped sustain American Motors during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p02] While the Rambler marque had been dropped in the United States after the 1969 model year, all export markets retained the Rambler name, with the longest to retain it being Mexico until 1983.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The initial building was built during 1926–27 by the Electric Refrigeration Corporation (subsequently Nash-Kelvinator) with design by Amedeo Leoni, industrial layout by Wallace McKenzie, and tower enclosure and industrial units by William E.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] War Department contracted with Nash-Kelvinator to produce 900 Sikorsky R-6 model helicopters.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] As part of that contract, a 4.5 acres (1.8 ha) site north of the factory was used as the smallest airport in the world as a flight testing base.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] Nash-Kelvinator produced about 50 R-6s a month during the war.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] When the contract was terminated at the war's end, 262 helicopters had been constructed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] During Chrysler's occupancy of the complex, it was known as Jeep and (Dodge) Truck Engineering (JTE), including facilities for body-on-frame work as well as testing facilities and labs.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The buildings included 1,500,000 square feet (140,000 m2), approximately one-third devoted to engineering and computer functions.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] As of 2007, Chrysler employed over 1,600 people at the complex, moving those operations in mid-2009 to the Chrysler Technology Center.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The property was put up for sale by Chrysler in early 2010.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was bought by a local man who gutted the building for scrap and left it in a dilapidated state before losing it to foreclosure.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The abandoned building was in possession of the city of Detroit and officials were considering if the industrial site would be more marketable if the building was torn down.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 2018, the Wayne County Commission approved a land swap that included a new jail complex for the county as well as a potential revival for the old American Motors building.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The era of 1900 until 1925 saw various corporations, in several U.S. states, use similar "American" names, such as American Motor Carriage Company (Ohio, 1902–1903), American Automobile Manufacturing Company (Indiana, 1911–1912), and American Motors Incorporated (New York, 1919–1920).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1916, an earlier "American Motors Corporation", apparently unrelated to the more famous later corporation of the same name, was formed in Newark, New Jersey, with Louis Chevrolet as vice president and chief engineer.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] By 1918, it was producing cars in a plant at Plainfield, New Jersey.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] In 1923, it merged with the Bessemer Motor Truck Company of Pennsylvania into Bessemer–American Motors Corporation, which lasted less than a year before merging with the Winther and Northway companies into Amalgamated Motors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] A new company was formed in Palmdale, California, in 2001.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] Registration for the American Motors trademarks was filed in 2001 by this California-based firm.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The company's website specifically claimed no affiliation to the previous American Motors but used American Motors' history and logos on its website.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The website is now dead, and the company's claims to American Motors' trademarks expired in 2005.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The new Chrysler LLC holds a live registration for the name "American Motors", which was applied for in 2005.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The "AMC" wordmark, complete with "A-mark" graphic logo, as was originally used in 1970 and through the late-1980s, was registered and published for comment by Chrysler as of 2010.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] Also: Kaiser Jeeps used the AMC 327, Buick 225 ("Dauntless V6"), Buick 350 ("Dauntless V8"), and Willys 134 I4 ("Hurricane").
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The downsized Jeep XJ Cherokee/Wagoneer used the Chevrolet 2.8 L V6 in 1983–1984.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors contracted with Volkswagen to buy tooling for the Audi 2.0 L OHC I4.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] Major parts (block, crankshaft, head assembly) were initially purchased from Audi and shipped to the U.S., where American Motors accomplished final assembly at a plant explicitly purchased for the production of this engine.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] Sales never reached numbers to justify taking over total production.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors made several changes to the engine.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] By contractual agreement, they were prevented from using the Volkswagen or Audi names in association with the American Motors assembled version.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] American Motors models historically regarded by hobbyists as particularly "collectible" include the Javelin, AMX, and performance specials such as the 1957 Rambler Rebel, 1965–67 Marlin, 1969 Hurst SC/Rambler, 1970 Rebel Machine, and 1971 Hornet SC/360.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] These models enjoyed limited popularity when new, resulting in low production figures.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] In January 2007, the AMC AMX was "really taking off in the muscle car market" according to the editors of *Hemmings Classic Car*, and it had "left its mark among AMC collectors' minds as a great alternative" to higher-priced Hemi-powered muscle cars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The early Javelin (1968–70) stands out from the Ford, General Motors, and Chrysler pony cars.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays, automotive historian and author of *The Savvy Guide to Buying Collector Cars at Auction*, the "Wow!
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] Factor" is an important and measurable pleasure to an owner whether their car is driven or sits in a climate-controlled garage.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] Moreover, the author's collector car, a 1969 Ambassador station wagon, made friends as strangers came to greet and host him as if "long lost kin".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] Mays points out the ready availability of parts for American Motors engines and his experiences in having service done on Ramblers without being charged for the work in exchange for the experience of driving a "sassy Rambler" (a 1966 American convertible) and having pictures taken with it.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] Other American Motors models, once somewhat ignored by the hobby, are now considered "future collectibles".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] Examples include the 1959 Ambassador 4-door hardtop station wagon, of which only 578 were produced, and the Jeep Scrambler CJ8, a combined pickup truck-Jeep, of which only a few thousand were made.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Gremlin is described as having "a cult-like following" in today's collectible car market.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The Gremlin shares components with some other American Motors models, making its repair and restoration relatively inexpensive compared with other "historic cars".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The AMC Pacer increased in value according to a Pacer owner who is the CEO of a major insurance provider for collector car owners.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] There are active Rambler and American Motors car clubs in the U.S. and elsewhere (examples in External Links).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] In April 2008, *Hot Rod* magazine released an article claiming that American Motors was in the process of being revived.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] The vehicles in the works were to be the AMX, Matador, Ambassador, Pacer, and Gremlin.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] It was a popular article, illustrated with drawings of the concept cars entering production and accompanied by plentiful information.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-motors-corporation-p03] However, it was later revealed as an April Fools' joke.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] The company was founded by Heinz Prechter in Los Angeles, California as the **American Sunroof Company** in 1965.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] In 2004, the aftermarket sunroof business was sold to Inalfa, and the company changed its name from American Sunroof Company to American Specialty Cars, with a "new emphasis on handling design, engineering and manufacturing of low-volume niche vehicles".
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] The company sold off much of its specialty equipment in 2014, when they experienced financial difficulties.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] All employees were terminated in 2017, its remaining assets having been sold to Roush Industries, and ASC ceased operations.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] In 1983 the Ford Flair ASC Concept was presented, built by ASC.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] The first generation Saab 900 cabriolet was developed by ASC and first unveiled as a 1983 concept car.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] In 1984 ASC built and marketed the ASC McLaren, a convertible version of the Mercury Capri, licensing the McLaren brand.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] In 1984, ASC built a concept car called the Vision, featuring a glass roof with a semi circular sunroof that dropped down and rotated to sit below the roof glass.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] From 1989, ASC manufactured the Porsche 944 Cabriolet at its factory in Weinsberg, Germany.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] In 1993 ASC created a Cadillac Seville coupe concept car.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] In 1994 ASC and Heuliez built a prototype for a Citroen ZX convertible.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/american-sunroof-company] In 2004 ASC unveiled the Helios concept, a four-door convertible version of the Chrysler 300C.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] An **anti-lock braking system** (**ABS**) is a safety anti-skid braking system used on aircraft and on land vehicles, such as cars, motorcycles, trucks, and buses.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] ABS operates by preventing the wheels from locking up during braking, thereby maintaining tractive contact with the road surface and allowing the driver to maintain more control over the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] ABS is an automated system that uses the principles of threshold braking and cadence braking, techniques which were once practiced by skillful drivers before ABS was widespread.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] ABS operates at a much faster rate and more effectively than most drivers could manage.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Although ABS generally offers improved vehicle control and decreases stopping distances on dry and some slippery surfaces, on loose gravel or snow-covered surfaces ABS may significantly increase braking distance, while still improving steering control.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Since ABS was introduced in production vehicles, such systems have become increasingly sophisticated and effective.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Modern versions may not only prevent wheel lock under braking, but may also alter the front-to-rear brake bias.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] This latter function, depending on its specific capabilities and implementation, is known variously as electronic brakeforce distribution, traction control system, emergency brake assist, or electronic stability control (ESC).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The concept for ABS predates the modern systems that were introduced in the 1950s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Francis introduced his 'Slip Prevention Regulator for Rail Vehicles'.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In 1920 the French automobile and aircraft pioneer Gabriel Voisin experimented with systems that modulated the hydraulic braking pressure on his aircraft brakes to reduce the risk of tire slippage, as threshold braking on aircraft is nearly impossible.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] These systems used a flywheel and valve attached to a hydraulic line that feeds the brake cylinders.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The flywheel is attached to a drum that runs at the same speed as the wheel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In normal braking, the drum and flywheel should spin at the same speed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] However, when a wheel slows down, then the drum would do the same, leaving the flywheel spinning at a faster rate.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] This causes the valve to open, allowing a small amount of brake fluid to bypass the master cylinder into a local reservoir, lowering the pressure on the cylinder and releasing the brakes.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The use of the drum and flywheel meant the valve only opened when the wheel was turning.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In testing, a 30% improvement in braking performance was noted, because the pilots immediately applied full brakes instead of slowly increasing pressure in order to find the skid point.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] An additional benefit was the elimination of burned or burst tires.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The first proper recognition of the ABS system came later with the German engineer Karl Wässel, whose system for modulating braking power was officially patented in 1928.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Wässel, however, never developed a working product and neither did Robert Bosch who produced a similar patent eight years later.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] A similar braking system called Decelostat that used direct-current generators to measure wheel slippage was used in railroads in the 1930s.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] By 1951, flywheel-based Decelostat was used in aircraft to provide anti skid in landings.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The device was on trials first in the United States and later by the British.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In 1954, *Popular Science* revealed that there was preliminary testing of the Decelostat system to prevent car swirling on a heavy brake by the US car manufacturers in Detroit.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] However, there was no public information of the test results.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Maxaret, while reducing braking distances by up to 30% in icy or wet conditions, also increased tire life, and had the additional advantage of allowing take-offs and landings in conditions that would preclude flying at all in non-Maxaret equipped aircraft.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In 1958, a Royal Enfield Super Meteor motorcycle was used by the Road Research Laboratory to test the Maxaret anti-lock brake.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The experiments demonstrated that anti-lock brakes can be of great value to motorcycles, for which skidding is involved in a high proportion of accidents.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Stopping distances were reduced in most of the tests compared with locked wheel braking, particularly on slippery surfaces, in which the improvement could be as much as 30%.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Enfield's technical director at the time, Tony Wilson-Jones, saw little future in the system, however, and it was not put into production by the company.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] A fully-mechanical system saw limited automobile use in the 1960s in the Ferguson P99 racing car, the Jensen FF, and the experimental all-wheel drive Ford Zodiac, but saw no further use; the system proved expensive and unreliable.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The first fully-electronic anti-lock braking system was developed in the late-1960s for the Concorde aircraft.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The modern ABS system was invented in 1971 by Mario Palazzetti (known as 'Mister ABS') in the Fiat Research Center and has become standard in almost every car.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The system was called Antiskid and the patent was sold to Bosch who named it ABS.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Chrysler, together with the Bendix Corporation, introduced a computerized, three-channel, four-sensor all-wheel ABS called "Sure Brake" for its 1971 Imperial.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] It was available for several years thereafter, functioned as intended, and proved reliable.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In 1969, Ford introduced an anti-lock braking system called "Sure-Track" to the rear wheels of the Lincoln Continental Mark III and Ford Thunderbird, as an option; it became standard in 1971.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The Sure-Track braking system was designed with help from Kelsey-Hayes.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In 1971, General Motors introduced the "Trackmaster" rear-wheel only ABS as an option on their rear-wheel drive Cadillac models and called the option the True-Track Braking System on the Oldsmobile Toronado.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In 1972, the option was made available in all Cadillacs.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In 1971, Nissan offered an EAL (Electro Anti-lock System) developed by Japanese company Denso as an option on the Nissan President, which became Japan's first electronic ABS.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] 1971: The Imperial became the first production car with a 4 wheel computer-operated anti-lock braking system.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Toyota introduced electronically controlled anti-skid brakes on Toyota Crown labeled as ESC (Electronic Skid Control).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] 1971: First truck application: "Antislittamento" system developed by *Fiat Veicoli Industriali* and installed on Fiat truck model 691N1.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] 1972: four-wheel-drive Triumph 2500 Estates were fitted with Mullard electronic systems as standard.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Such cars were rare however and very few remain.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] 1976: WABCO began the development of the anti-locking braking system on commercial vehicles to prevent locking on slippery roads, followed in 1986 by the electronic braking system (EBS) for heavy-duty vehicles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] 1978: Mercedes-Benz W116 As one of the firsts, used an electronic four-wheel multi-channel anti-lock braking system (ABS) from Bosch as an option from 1978 on.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] 1982: Honda introduced electronically controlled multi-channel ALB (Anti Locking Brakes) as an option for the second generation of Prelude, launched worldwide in 1982.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Additional info: the general agent for Honda in Norway required all Preludes for the Norwegian market to have the ALB-system as a standard feature, making Honda Prelude be the first car delivered in Europe with ABS as a standard feature.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The Norwegian general agent also included a sunroof and other options to be standard equipment in Norway, adding more luxury to the Honda brand.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] However, the Norwegian tax system made the well-equipped car very expensive, and the sales suffered from high costs.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] From 1984 the ALB-system, as well as the other optional features from Honda, was no longer a standard feature in Norway.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In 1985 the Ford Scorpio was introduced to the European market with a Teves electronic system throughout the range as standard.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] For this the model was awarded the coveted European Car of the Year Award in 1986, with very favorable praise from motoring journalists.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] After this success, Ford began research into Anti-Lock systems for the rest of their range, which encouraged other manufacturers to follow suit.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Since 1987 ABS has been standard equipment on all Mercedes-Benz automobiles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In 1988, BMW introduced the first motorcycle with an electro-hydraulic ABS: the BMW K100.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Yamaha Introduced the FJ1200 model with optional ABS in 1991.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Honda followed suit in 1992 with the launch of its first motorcycle ABS on the ST1100 Pan European.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In 2007, Suzuki launched its GSF1200SA (Bandit) with an ABS.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] In 2005, Harley-Davidson began offering an ABS option on police bikes.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The anti-lock brake controller is also known as the CAB (Controller Anti-lock Brake).
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Typically ABS includes a central electronic control unit (ECU), four wheel speed sensors, and at least two hydraulic valves within the brake hydraulics.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Conversely, if the ECU detects a wheel turning significantly faster than the others, brake hydraulic pressure to the wheel is increased so the braking force is reapplied, slowing down the wheel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] This process is repeated continuously and can be detected by the driver via brake pedal pulsation.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Some anti-lock systems can apply or release braking pressure 15 times per second.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Because of this, the wheels of cars equipped with ABS are practically impossible to lock even during panic braking in extreme conditions.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The ECU is programmed to disregard differences in wheel rotative speed below a critical threshold because when the car is turning, the two wheels towards the center of the curve turn slower than the outer two.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] For this same reason, a differential is used in virtually all roadgoing vehicles.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] If a fault develops in any part of the ABS, a warning light will usually be illuminated on the vehicle instrument panel, and the ABS will be disabled until the fault is rectified.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Modern ABS applies individual brake pressure to all four wheels through a control system of hub-mounted sensors and a dedicated micro-controller.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] ABS is offered or comes standard on most road vehicles and is the foundation for electronic stability control systems, which are rapidly increasing in popularity due to the great reduction in the price of vehicle electronics over the years.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Modern electronic stability control (ESC) systems are an evolution of the ABS concept.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Here, a minimum of two additional sensors are added to help the system work: these are a steering wheel angle sensor and a gyroscopic sensor.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The steering wheel sensor also helps in the operation of Cornering Brake Control (CBC), since this will tell the ABS that wheels on the inside of the curve should brake more than wheels on the outside, and by how much.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] ABS equipment may also be used to implement a traction control system (TCS) on the acceleration of the vehicle.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] If, when accelerating, the tire loses traction, the ABS controller can detect the situation and take suitable action so that traction is regained.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] More sophisticated versions of this can also control throttle levels and brakes simultaneously.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The speed sensors of ABS are sometimes used in indirect tire pressure monitoring system (TPMS), which can detect under-inflation of the tire(s) by the difference in the rotational speed of wheels.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] There are four main components of ABS: wheel speed sensors, valves, a pump, and a controller.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] A speed sensor is used to determine the acceleration or deceleration of the wheel.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The rotation of the wheel or differential induces a magnetic field around the sensor.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The fluctuations of this magnetic field generate a voltage in the sensor.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Since the voltage induced in the sensor is a result of the rotating wheel, this sensor can become inaccurate at slow speeds.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The slower rotation of the wheel can cause inaccurate fluctuations in the magnetic field and thus cause inaccurate readings to the controller.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] There is a valve in the brake line of each brake controlled by the ABS.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The majority of problems with the valve system occur due to clogged valves.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] When a valve is clogged it is unable to open, close, or change position.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] An inoperable valve will prevent the system from modulating the valves and controlling pressure supplied to the brakes.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The pump in the ABS is used to restore the pressure to the hydraulic brakes after the valves have released it.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] A signal from the controller will release the valve at the detection of wheel slip.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] After a valve releases the pressure supplied from the user, the pump is used to restore the desired amount of pressure to the braking system.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The controller will modulate the pump's status in order to provide the desired amount of pressure and reduce slipping.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] type unit in the car which receives information from each individual wheel speed sensor.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] If a wheel loses traction, the signal is sent to the controller.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The controller will then limit the brake force (EBD) and activate the ABS modulator which actuates the braking valves on and off.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] There are many different variations and control algorithms for use in ABS.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The ABS controller knows that such a rapid deceleration of the car is impossible (and in actuality the rapid deceleration means the wheel is about to slip), so it reduces the pressure to that brake until it sees an acceleration, then it increases the pressure until it sees the deceleration again.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] It can do this very quickly before the wheel can actually significantly change speed.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The result is that the wheel slows down at the same rate as the car, with the brakes keeping the wheels very near the point at which they will start to lock up.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] This gives the system maximum braking power.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] This replaces the need to manually pump the brakes while driving on a slippery or a low traction surface, allowing to steer even in most emergency braking conditions.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] When the ABS is in operation the driver will feel a pulsing in the brake pedal; this comes from the rapid opening and closing of the valves.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] This pulsing also tells the driver that the ABS has been triggered.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Anti-lock braking systems use different schemes depending on the type of brakes in use.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] They can be differentiated by the number of channels: that is, how many valves that are individually controlled—and the number of speed sensors.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] There is a speed sensor on all four wheels and a separate valve for all four wheels.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] With this setup, the controller monitors each wheel individually to make sure it is achieving maximum braking force.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] There is a speed sensor on all four wheels and a separate valve for each of the front wheels, but only one valve for both of the rear wheels.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] Older vehicles with four-wheel ABS usually use this type.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] This scheme, commonly found on pickup trucks with four-wheel ABS, has a speed sensor and a valve for each of the front wheels, with one valve and one sensor for both rear wheels.
[src:chrysler-new-yorker/anti-lock-brakes] The speed sensor for the rear wheels is located in the rear axle.
